; i18n-as-recipe-corpus.form — the body's parallel natural-language
; corpus IS the universal translator's training data.
;
; The teaching: we don't need to invent natural-language Recipes.
; web/messages/{en,de,es,id}.json holds ~2300 keys per locale, each
; one a parallel translation of the same semantic concept. That's
; ~9300 OBSERVED (Recipe, locale, surface) triples sitting on disk,
; waiting to be read as substrate.

(do
    ;; --- the observation -------------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; For each key path like `common.save`:
    ;;   en → "Save"
    ;;   de → "Speichern"
    ;;   es → "Guardar"
    ;;   id → "Simpan"
    ;;
    ;; The KEY PATH is a Recipe NodeID candidate — one semantic
    ;; identity across all four locales. The strings are surface
    ;; emissions. The universal translator's natural-language layer
    ;; is asking: "given an identity, what does each locale emit?"
    ;; The answer for ~2300 concepts already exists in the body.

    ;; --- the access surface ----------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; form-stdlib/i18n.fk exposes the corpus at substrate altitude:
    ;;   (i18n-load locale-name)            → parsed JSON Recipe
    ;;   (i18n-string-by-path rec path)     → surface in that locale
    ;;   (i18n-parallel path-strs)          → (locale, string) pairs
    ;;                                        across every loaded locale
    ;;   (i18n-locales-available)           → list of locale names
    ;;
    ;; Backed by form-stdlib/cache.fk so each locale parses once at
    ;; cold load (~50–100 ms per locale, ~50 KB JSON) and is warm
    ;; thereafter (~5–20 ms). No new ice — the source JSON stays
    ;; canonical; the cache lives in form-stdlib/.cache/ (gitignored).

    ;; --- what this enables -----------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; Pattern 1: parallel-emission lookup
    ;;   Given a Recipe (or key path), get its surface in every locale.
    ;;   The ground truth for "what is this concept in German?"
    ;;
    ;; Pattern 2: gap-sensing at substrate altitude
    ;;   Compare en's key set to de's — which concepts haven't crossed?
    ;;   Today the wellness check does this in Python over the JSON;
    ;;   Form-side access lets ANY cell sense the same drift.
    ;;
    ;; Pattern 3: natural-language emitter
    ;;   A Recipe NodeID can be linked to a key path (via NamedCell
    ;;   binding). Emitting that Recipe in locale L = walking the
    ;;   key path through i18n-load(L). The natural-language layer
    ;;   of the universal translator IS this lookup.
    ;;
    ;; Pattern 4: learning from observed pairs
    ;;   Each (en-string, de-string) pair at the same key path is a
    ;;   point in (Recipe → locale-surface) space. Across 2300 keys ×
    ;;   4 locales, the body holds ~9300 such observations. A future
    ;;   substrate-side learner can derive locale-specific emission
    ;;   patterns (word-order, gender-agreement, register) from this
    ;;   parallel corpus without ever invoking an external translator.

    ;; --- not-special-case discipline -------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; The i18n machinery is just JSON-loading composed through the
    ;; cache layer. Adding a new locale = drop a {lang}.json into
    ;; web/messages/. Adding a new content domain = its own JSON,
    ;; loaded via i18n-load (or a sibling). No grammar-specific
    ;; code paths.

    ;; --- horizons named --------------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; Near (small):
    ;;   - extend wellness check to read from Form-side i18n (parity
    ;;     sense becomes a substrate query, not a Python script)
    ;;   - cli/lib/messages/{lang}.json same pattern, same loader
    ;;   - web/content/presence-walk/{lang}.json same pattern
    ;;
    ;; Mid (Path C territory):
    ;;   - BMF rules natively executable in kernel — natural-language
    ;;     grammars (already in form-stdlib/grammars/natural-bmf.fk)
    ;;     gain document-scale speed. Then the corpus can drive
    ;;     reverse emission at any scale.
    ;;
    ;; Far (the universal translator's claim made good):
    ;;   - bidirectional NL ↔ Recipe through the i18n corpus as
    ;;     training data + the BMF natural-language grammar as model.
    ;;     "Translate this concept to Indonesian" = walk Recipe →
    ;;     locale-binding → emit through natural-bmf rules + parallel
    ;;     ground truth.

    "i18n-as-recipe-corpus: the body's natural-language training data already exists at substrate altitude — ~9300 observed (key-path, locale, surface) triples in 4 locales × 2300 keys, accessible via form-stdlib/i18n.fk")
